<div class="rankings container container--narrow">
  <h1 class="rankings-heading">The List</h1>
  <p class="rankings-intro">Personal rankings, updated as we eat. No sponsored placements, no aggregated scores — just the places we would send someone I trust with no time to waste.</p>

  <ol class="rankings-list">

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/toyosu-sushi/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">1</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1717988732486-285ea23a6f88?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Sukiyabashi Jiro Honten" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Tokyo &mdash; Ginza</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Sukiyabashi Jiro Honten</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">The most considered sushi counter in the country; Jiro Ono's omakase has defined the genre for thirty years and still has nothing to prove.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/nagoya-meshi/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">2</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547592180-85f173990554?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Atsuta Horaiken" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Nagoya &mdash; Atsuta</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Atsuta Horaiken</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Hitsumabushi eel served in three passes since 1873 — the definitive expression of Nagoya's most original dish, and worth the queue.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/kyoto-food-scene/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">3</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1764888802295-648490e594dd?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Nakamura" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Kyoto &mdash; Central</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Nakamura</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Operating since 1716, the kaiseki here is a weekly-changing argument about what is in season and why it matters, served in ceramics chosen to make the point.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/tempura/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">4</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1570078362689-c57c33cca104?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Kondo" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Tokyo &mdash; Ginza</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Kondo</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Fumio Kondo's vegetable tempura counter; the sweet potato in autumn and the fiddlehead fern in spring are as good as this cooking style gets.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/tempura/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">5</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1677743537607-f7fc9273ec4d?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Mikawa Zezankyo" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Tokyo &mdash; Fukagawa</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Mikawa Zezankyo</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Tetsuya Saotome's tempura counter in a converted townhouse — technically flawless, ingredient-led, and difficult to book for good reason.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/fukuoka-yatai/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">6</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1749894274841-95fa78941841?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Shin-Shin" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Fukuoka &mdash; Nakasu</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Shin-Shin</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">The Hakata tonkotsu benchmark: milky broth, thin noodles, minimal toppings — a bowl that makes the case for restraint in a style not known for it.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/sapporo-ramen/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">7</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1569718212165-3a8278d5f624?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Aji no Karyu" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Sapporo &mdash; Susukino</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Aji no Karyu</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">One of the original Ramen Yokocho shops, open since 1951; the miso broth in February, after ten minutes in the cold, is worth the flight to Hokkaido.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/ramen-regions/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">8</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1614563637806-1d0e645e0940?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Fuunji" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Tokyo &mdash; Shinjuku</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Fuunji</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">The fish-forward tsukemen counter that changed what people expected from Tokyo ramen; the dipping broth is concentrated enough to stand a spoon in.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/kagawa-udon/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">9</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1583623025817-d180a2221d0a?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Udon Baka Ichidai" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Kagawa &mdash; Takamatsu</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Udon Baka Ichidai</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Self-service, open early, closed when the noodles run out — the kama-tama here is the reason to make the trip to Shikoku.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/kyoto-food-scene/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">10</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1578399337856-c661ba5e5cec?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Izusen" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Kyoto &mdash; Daitokuji</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Izusen</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Shojin ryori in red lacquer bowls, served in the grounds of a temple, where the meat-free constraint produces more creativity than most full kitchens manage.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/ramen-regions/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">11</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1614563637806-1d0e645e0940?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Taishoken" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Tokyo &mdash; Ikebukuro</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Taishoken</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">The original tsukemen shop — Kazuo Yamagishi invented the format here in 1961, and the bowl has stayed honest to itself ever since.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/nagoya-meshi/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">12</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547592180-85f173990554?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Yabaton" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Nagoya &mdash; Citywide</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Yabaton</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">Miso katsu since 1947; the Hatcho miso sauce over a properly fried cutlet is the dish that makes the Nagoya-meshi case most efficiently.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/kanazawa-seafood/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">13</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1611762687807-7cdd09aef422?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Omicho Shokudo" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Kanazawa &mdash; Omicho</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Omicho Shokudo</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">The lunch counter above the market, where the morning's catch from the Sea of Japan determines the menu and the nodoguro sells out first.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/tempura/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">14</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1570078362689-c57c33cca104?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Tsunahachi" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Tokyo &mdash; Shinjuku</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Tsunahachi</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">The honest case for mid-range tempura: open since 1923, consistent, fairly priced, and a reliable indicator of what the form should taste like at its baseline.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

    <li class="rankings-item">
      <a class="rankings-item-link" href="/posts/kagawa-udon/">
        <span class="rankings-rank">15</span>
        <img class="rankings-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1583623025817-d180a2221d0a?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Nakamura Udon" />
        <div class="rankings-body">
          <div class="rankings-name-row">
            <div class="rankings-location">Kagawa &mdash; Utazu</div>
            <div class="rankings-price">$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="rankings-name">Nakamura Udon</div>
          <p class="rankings-desc">A rural shop that requires effort to reach and rewards the effort with the kind of koshi that makes Sanuki udon's reputation feel, if anything, understated.</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </li>

  </ol>
</div>
